WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:20.000
Cryptanalysis, the art and science of breaking cryptosystems

00:30.000 --> 00:40.000
Cryptanalysis, the art and science of breaking cryptosystems

00:40.000 --> 00:46.000
of cracking codes, of trying to figure out how to break these very cool cryptographic algorithms

00:46.000 --> 00:50.000
that we spent all this time talking about. And when I say the art and the science,

00:50.000 --> 00:54.000
that's quite true. It takes a very clever, very devious mind to try and figure out

00:54.000 --> 00:58.000
how to break cryptographic systems. There are two categories of cryptanalysis

00:58.000 --> 01:02.000
that we're going to look at. Cryptanalytical attacks and cryptographic attacks.

01:02.000 --> 01:06.000
In this module, we're going to focus on cryptanalytical attacks.

01:06.000 --> 01:10.000
So when we say cryptanalytical attacks, what do we mean?

01:10.000 --> 01:14.000
What is the primary goal of all cryptanalytical attacks?

01:14.000 --> 01:18.000
And this is actually really important to understand.

01:18.000 --> 01:20.000
Because when you're thinking about these different types of attacks,

01:20.000 --> 01:24.000
if you understand what you're always after, what the primary goal is,

01:24.000 --> 01:26.000
it makes a lot of you understand how you're going about it.

01:26.000 --> 01:32.000
The primary goal of all cryptanalytical attacks is to deduce the key.

01:32.000 --> 01:36.000
Figure out what the key is that's being used in the cryptosystem.

01:36.000 --> 01:38.000
Let's talk about brute force attacks.

01:38.000 --> 01:40.000
Brute force attacks are very simple.

01:40.000 --> 01:44.000
You try every single possible key until you find the right key.

01:44.000 --> 01:48.000
But while they're simple, they're not very effective in modern day cryptography.

01:48.000 --> 01:52.000
Because as soon as you get a key length of a reasonable size,

01:52.000 --> 01:56.000
trying to find the one specific key that you're looking for to brute force a key

01:56.000 --> 01:58.000
is not a realistic type of attack.

01:58.000 --> 02:02.000
So here's an interesting table that we're showing you here.

02:02.000 --> 02:04.000
This shows you a few pieces of information.

02:04.000 --> 02:08.000
The proper name for this first column would be the key length.

02:08.000 --> 02:12.000
It's the number. It's the number of bits and the key.

02:12.000 --> 02:14.000
The second column is showing you the number of keys.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.000
Better name for that would be the key space.

02:16.000 --> 02:20.000
And the third column is telling you the attack time.

02:20.000 --> 02:22.000
Now here's the interesting thing behind this.

02:22.000 --> 02:26.000
This attack time is based on a system that was built in 1999,

02:26.000 --> 02:30.000
specifically to brute force des.

02:30.000 --> 02:36.000
So in 1999, the EFF spent $250,000 to build a system.

02:36.000 --> 02:38.000
Best name system ever, Deepcrack.

02:38.000 --> 02:42.000
So they built a system in 1999 called Deepcrack,

02:42.000 --> 02:46.000
specifically designed to break des and to brute force a des key.

02:46.000 --> 02:50.000
In 1999, it took 20 hours to brute force a des key.

02:50.000 --> 02:54.000
Now, our modern day systems have gotten significantly faster

02:54.000 --> 02:56.000
than what we had in 1999,

02:56.000 --> 02:58.000
orders of magnitude faster.

02:58.000 --> 03:02.000
But even so, it doesn't matter.

03:02.000 --> 03:06.000
So a modern day system could brute force a des key in minutes, maybe hours.

03:06.000 --> 03:10.000
But once you start to increase the key length,

03:10.000 --> 03:12.000
if you increase the key length by even one bit,

03:12.000 --> 03:14.000
what happens to the key space?

03:14.000 --> 03:16.000
It doubles.

03:16.000 --> 03:18.000
And so it grows exponentially.

03:18.000 --> 03:20.000
And by the time we get up to 128-bit,

03:20.000 --> 03:22.000
even especially 256-bit keys,

03:22.000 --> 03:24.000
the concept that you could possibly brute force that key is

03:24.000 --> 03:26.000
completely absurd.

03:26.000 --> 03:28.000
And here's a way to think of that,

03:28.000 --> 03:32.000
to understand how insanely impossible it is to try and brute force

03:32.000 --> 03:34.000
a 256-bit key.

03:34.000 --> 03:36.000
We need to think of some sort of way of wrapping our head around,

03:36.000 --> 03:40.000
just how big is the key space for a 256-bit key?

03:40.000 --> 03:42.000
So here's a way to think about it, okay?

03:42.000 --> 03:44.000
Think about the number of atoms.

03:44.000 --> 03:48.000
So there's a lot of atoms in, say, a person.

03:48.000 --> 03:50.000
Now, when we talk about a 256-bit key,

03:50.000 --> 03:56.000
the key space is 1.15, 1.15 times 10 to the 77th.

03:56.000 --> 03:58.000
That's the key space.

03:58.000 --> 04:00.000
That's a huge number.

04:00.000 --> 04:02.000
How big is that?

04:02.000 --> 04:04.000
Well, if we compare it to the number of atoms,

04:04.000 --> 04:08.000
the number of atoms in the human body is only 10 to the 27th.

04:08.000 --> 04:10.000
Again, we're looking for 10 to the 77th.

04:10.000 --> 04:12.000
No, we're near close.

04:12.000 --> 04:14.000
Okay, well, what about the number of atoms in the earth?

04:14.000 --> 04:18.000
Well, that's only 10 to the 50th.

04:18.000 --> 04:20.000
Again, no, we're near close.

04:20.000 --> 04:22.000
Okay, so what about the number of atoms in the

04:22.000 --> 04:26.000
our solar system, the Sun, Earth, Neptune, Mars,

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
all the matter in our little solar system?

04:30.000 --> 04:32.000
That's only 10 to the 52nd.

04:32.000 --> 04:34.000
Again, no, we're near close.

04:34.000 --> 04:38.000
You have to actually get up to the entire observable universe.

04:38.000 --> 04:42.000
That's about 10 to the 79th atoms in the entire observable universe.

04:42.000 --> 04:46.000
That's an insanely large number.

04:46.000 --> 04:50.000
When someone says to you, oh, we're going to brute force a 256-bit key,

04:50.000 --> 04:54.000
what they're essentially saying is that they're trying to find one

04:54.000 --> 04:58.000
and only one unique atom in the entire observable universe.

04:58.000 --> 05:00.000
It's insane.

05:00.000 --> 05:04.000
It is totally impossible with modern-day technology to possibly

05:04.000 --> 05:08.000
brute force a 50 to 256-bit key, and it's going to be impossible for quite a ways to go.

05:08.000 --> 05:10.000
So what are reasonable techniques that we could use?

05:10.000 --> 05:14.000
Well, let's go through a few other crypto-analytical attacks.

05:14.000 --> 05:16.000
And again, I'm going to remind you,

05:16.000 --> 05:20.000
the whole point of all these attacks is to deduce the key,

05:20.000 --> 05:22.000
figure out the key.

05:22.000 --> 05:26.000
Now, the first attack we're going to look at is what's known as a

05:26.000 --> 05:28.000
cypher-text-only attack.

05:28.000 --> 05:32.000
And as the name implies, all that the crypto-analysis has access to here,

05:32.000 --> 05:36.000
the only attack is just the cypher-text.

05:36.000 --> 05:38.000
So this is a very difficult type of an attack.

05:38.000 --> 05:42.000
The next is what's known as a plain-text attack.

05:42.000 --> 05:48.000
In a plain-text attack, the crypto-analysis actually has access to the cypher-text

05:48.000 --> 05:50.000
and the plain-text.

05:50.000 --> 05:53.000
So maybe a spy or someone like that smuggled out the plain-text.

05:53.000 --> 05:56.000
They pulled the cypher-text off the wire, so they have access to both.

05:56.000 --> 06:00.000
If the crypto-analysis already has the plain-text and the cypher-text,

06:00.000 --> 06:03.000
why are they doing anything to find the key?

06:03.000 --> 06:06.000
Because with the key, you can decode all the other messages

06:06.000 --> 06:09.000
and perhaps even forge your own messages.

06:09.000 --> 06:11.000
So that's a plain-text attack.

06:11.000 --> 06:16.000
Now, the next two attacks have the word chosen in them.

06:16.000 --> 06:18.000
Here's what chosen means.

06:18.000 --> 06:22.000
Chosen means the crypto-analysis has access to the machine or the algorithm

06:22.000 --> 06:25.000
that's performing the encryption.

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
And so, in a chosen plain-text attack,

06:28.000 --> 06:33.000
what that means is that the crypto-analysis is able to choose the plain-text

06:33.000 --> 06:35.000
that they feed into the machine or the algorithm,

06:35.000 --> 06:40.000
look at the result in cypher-text to determine, to deduce the key.

06:40.000 --> 06:45.000
Now, with modern algorithms that we use, des AES, so forth,

06:45.000 --> 06:48.000
do we know, do we have access to the algorithms?

06:48.000 --> 06:50.000
And the answer is absolutely yes.

06:50.000 --> 06:52.000
These modern-day algorithms, they're open source.

06:52.000 --> 06:56.000
So think of a chosen plain-text attack as you have access to the AES,

06:56.000 --> 06:57.000
AES algorithm.

06:57.000 --> 06:59.000
You choose what plain-text to feed into it.

06:59.000 --> 07:04.000
You look at the result in cypher-text to try and deduce the key.

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
The next one is known as a chosen cypher-text.

07:07.000 --> 07:10.000
And as you're probably guessing, a chosen cypher-text attack

07:10.000 --> 07:15.000
is where the crypto-analysis feeds in some cypher-text, some chosen cypher-text.

07:15.000 --> 07:20.000
Looks at the result in plain-text to try and deduce the key.

07:20.000 --> 07:25.000
Now, the next two types of attacks known as linear and differential.

07:26.000 --> 07:31.000
All you should really know about these is they are using complicated math to try and deduce the key.

07:31.000 --> 07:35.000
So you see linear, you see differential, just think, complicated math,

07:35.000 --> 07:38.000
complicated math to try and deduce the key.

07:38.000 --> 07:42.000
And the final one we'll talk about is what's known as a factoring attack.

07:42.000 --> 07:46.000
Now, what is the only algorithm that we talked about that used factoring

07:46.000 --> 07:48.000
as the hard math problem behind it?

07:48.000 --> 07:49.000
RSA.

07:49.000 --> 07:53.000
So if you see factoring as the hard, as a type of an crypto-analytical attack,

07:53.000 --> 07:56.000
the only algorithm that you need to think about is RSA.

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
So associate those in your mind.

